<h2><a name="TOC-The-difference-between-a-risk-owner-and-a-risk-actionee"></a>The difference between a risk owner and a risk actionee</h2>
<div>One a risk is identified it is assigned an <b>owner</b> who is responsible for all matters regarding this risk. They monitor it and should it require response action are also responsible for taking that action (perhaps more than one response). The risk owner is answerable to the Project Manager.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>If the response requires specialist knowledge or is quite simple and boring then it will be assigned to a risk <b>actionee</b> who carries out the response but is always answerable to the owner. The <b>actionee</b> can be considered the owner of <b>this required action</b>&nbsp;but there can be more than one action with different actionees.&nbsp;</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<p style="font-size:1.5em;font-style:italic;background-color:#bbc;text-align:center;margin-left:20%;margin-right:20%">Managing <b>uncertainty</b>
</p>
<h2><a name="TOC-The-purpose-of-the-Risk-theme"></a>The purpose of the Risk theme</h2>
<div></div>
<div class="sites-codeblock sites-codesnippet-block">
<div><code>The purpose of the Risk theme is to identify, assess and control <b>uncertainty</b> and, as a result, improve the ability of the project to succeed.</code></div>
<div></div>
</div>
<br>
<h2><a name="TOC-How-the-Risk-theme-supports-the-continued-business-justification-principle"></a>How the Risk theme supports the continued business justification principle</h2>
<div>A reminder of the <a href="/details/PRJ#TOC-CONTINUED-BUSINESS-JUSTIFICATION">continued business justification principle</a>.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>Risk management starts at the very beginning of PRINCE2 and is a continual activity carried out throughout the life of the project, without this, it would not be possible to have the confidence that the project is able to meet its objectives and should therefore be continued. In other words, risk management <b>threatens the Business Case</b> and hence the continued business justification principle.<br>
</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>In the Starting up the Project process, the project manager will use the Daily Log to capture and manage any known risks; these will be used as part of the <b>evidence put before the project board to decide whether or not to proceed</b>.<br>
</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div><b>Major risks</b> are included in the Business Case.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<img alt="Risks and continued business justification" border="0" src="/public/RISK_AND_CBJ.png" style="width:60%;float:right">
<div>During a project, say during Managing Product Delivery (doing the work), teams may identify risks. The Team Manager should inform the Project Manager (doing Controlling a Stage) of the Risk and the PM then adds it to the Risk Register (needs categorising from RMS, owner assigning etc).At Managing a Stage Boundary the Business Case may be updated to reflect this risk and then the Project Board will need to decide if the project <b>still has business justification</b>.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>The risks are <b>documented</b> in the Risk Register.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div><span style="font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">In the <b style="background-color:rgb(255,255,0)">Assess &gt; Evaluate</b> element of risk management the total net severity of risk is evaluated and this can be </span><b style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">compared to the tolerances set for risk</b><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5"> (one of the six aspects of management) and hence assist determination of <b>continued business justification</b>.</span></div>
<div><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5"><br>
</span></div>
<div><span style="background-color:transparent;font-size:1em;line-height:1.5">&nbsp;</span></div>
</div>
